<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-09-18T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-09-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="473" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">611.1831/66 Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Sack</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-09-18T13:00:00-04:00">September 18, 1935—1
                                    p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>35. With reference to your despatch No. 840, of September 6. You are
                            authorized to accept binding of the present rate on flour in view of
                            your opinion that insistence on a duty reduction will jeopardize
                            conclusion of the trade agreement. It is hoped that this substantial
                            modification of our position will clear the way for rapid and
                            satisfactory conclusion of the agreement.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
